Dynamite and "The Silent South": A Story from the Second Reconstruction in South Carolina -- tAfterwords -- tPortraying Power -- tReflections -- tThe Shoah and Southern History -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhite supremacy shaped all aspects of post-Civil War southern life, yet its power was never complete or total. The form of segregation and subjection nicknamed Jim Crow constantly had to remake itself over time even as white southern politicians struggled to extend its grip. Here, some of the most innovative scholars of southern history question Jim Crow's sway, evolution, and methods over the course of a century. These essays bring to life the southern men and women--some heroic and decent, others mean and sinister, most a mixture of both--who supported and challenged Jim Crow, showing that white supremacy always had to prove its power. Jim Crow was always in motion, always adjusting to meet resistance and defiance by both African Americans and whites. Sometimes white supremacists responded with increased ferocity, sometimes with more subtle political and legal ploys. Jumpin' Jim Crow presents a clear picture of this complex negotiation. For example, even as some black and white women launched the strongest attacks on the system, other white women nurtured myths glorifying white supremacy. Even as elite whites blamed racial violence on poor whites, they used Jim Crow to dominate poor whites as well as blacks. Most important, the book portrays change over time, suggesting that Strom Thurmond is not a simple reincarnation of Ben Tillman and that Rosa Parks was not the first black woman to say no to Jim Crow. From a study of the segregation of household consumption to a fresh look at critical elections, from an examination of an unlikely antilynching campaign to an analysis of how miscegenation laws tried to sexualize black political power, these essays about specific southern times and places exemplify the latest trends in historical research. Its rich, accessible content makes Jumpin' Jim Crow an ideal undergraduate reader on American history, while its methodological innovations will be emulated by scholars of political history generally. In addition to the editors, the contributors are Edward L. Ayers, Elsa Barkley Brown, W. Fitzhugh Brundage, Laura F. Edwards, Kari Frederickson, David F. Godshalk, Grace Elizabeth Hale, Jacquelyn Dowd Hall, Stephen Kantrowitz, Nancy MacLean, Nell Irwin Painter, and Timothy B. Tyson.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Feb 2021) 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rightszSouthern StatesxHistory. 0aSex rolezSouthern StatesxHistory. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh  aAbernathy, Mary.  aArkansas.  aBarnes, Mary.  aButler, Matthew.  aChamberlain, Daniel.  aDare, Virginia.  aDouglass, Frederick.  aEdmonds, Richard.  aEdwards, Griffin.  aForrester, Richard.  aGeorgia.  aHampton, Wade.  aHinton, Mary Hilliard.  aJews.  aJohnson, Andrew.  aLebsock, Suzanne.  aLittle Rock, Ark.  aMahone, William.  aMcFadden, Ida Caldwell.  aNew Deal.  aNorth Carolina.  aParker, John.  aProgressivism.  aSouth Carolina.  aanti-Semitism.  ablack codes.  achild labor.  aconsumption.  afederal intervention.  ageneral stores.  aministers.  apatronage.  aracial terrorism.1 aSimon, Bryant, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDailey, Jane, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGodshalk, David F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAyers, Edward L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarkley Brown, Elsa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGilmore, Glenda 